<h2>Optimizing Your Sleep Schedule for Learning</h2>
<p>The quality of your sleep directly affects how well you retain vocabulary. Deep sleep is when the brain consolidates declarative memories including new words and their meanings. REM sleep helps integrate new information with existing knowledge. For optimal vocabulary retention, aim for 7 to 9 hours of quality sleep with sufficient time in both sleep stages. Consistency in your sleep schedule also matters: going to bed and waking up at the same time each day supports the brain's natural consolidation cycles.</p>
<p>Avoid studying immediately before bed if you find that mental stimulation interferes with falling asleep. Instead, do your pre-sleep review at least 30 minutes before bedtime, then wind down with relaxing activities. This gives your brain time to begin the consolidation process without interference from new information arriving right at sleep onset.</p>

